message: Initial commit
Added start of SSP nav, loading, and rendering
EGRC-136; Rename OSCAL Browser to OSCAL Viewer
EGRC-140: Added test of component control implementation description
Update package.json to include lint script
update package.json to include format script
Fix import/no-extraneous-dependencies lint error

Create React library structure

To prepare EGRC for open source, a react library approach would be more
suitable for our project. Our OSCAL Viewer application framework is now
made separate from our components, loaders, and other library elements.

Use uuid to generate unique keys.

OSCALControl was using an index as a key for each OSCALControlPart
created. This is advised against by react. The parts being mapped do not
have a clear id or field to use as a unique key. Using uuid is the next
best way of giving each child element of a list a unique key that
persists until the child is recreated.

Update README.md and instruction documentation

To better understand how the project works after the recent structure
change, the OSCAL React Library instructions has been updated.
This includes information about running and testing, as well as
the added scripts.

Merge remote-tracking branch 'origin/develop' into EGRC-168

Fix merging issues

EGRC-168 made some very major changes. In order to merge EGRC-412 into
develop, they had to be merged. Changes to OSCALLoader & the
package-lock files were also needed.

Set up Storybook documentation for Control Components

Made inital setup for writing Storybook docs and
wrote up docs for components related to OSCAL Controls.

Added .stories.js files to the src/stories directory for
each component. These files render the components in the
Storybook stories.

Created a markdown page at src/stories/OSCALDocs.stories.mdx
that can serve as an initial framework for documenting the
Storybook page.
This will include a short description of each control
and the required and optional props for each one.

Fix Testing Dependency Issue with Storybook

Added "@testing-library/dom" to dependecies in
package.json in order to fix the broken tests.
Seems the storybook init command "npx sb init" was
also overwriting and deleting this dependency. Adding
it explicity to package.json keeps it from doing that.

Remove Unneeded Rules from Package

Some override rules were added to package.json when
setting up Storybook.
These are removed to clean up the code.

Publish Both Library and Viewer to GitHub Packages

Updated the GitHub actions config and root package.json to
configure publishing the React Library to GitHub packages
along with the Viewer.
This will continously publish the React Library and set things up
to eventually publish to a public registry.

Replace npm install with npm ci

Replace, in workflow and project build files, npm
install with npm ci, unless the npm install is a
global installation. This solves unexpected pipeline
failures and provides information on which
dependencies need to be added, if any.

Revert some changes from install to ci

Revert some changes made in package.json that used npm ci
instead of npm install because those scripts were only used
by developers and not in an actual workflow run

Merge pull request #168 from EasyDynamics/EGRC-492

Configure Publishing OSCAL Viewer to GitHub Packages

Rename Package to Include Scope

Changed the name field in package.json to include the GitHub organization
name to be able to publish to the GitHub npm registry.

Test npm command

Run npm version patch in the example
directory to see if desired changes
have the desired impact on the
oscal-viewer package version.

Update workflow permissions

Update workflow permissions to allow for the
modification of files during a workflow run.

Add files to be committed in actions

Stage files to be committed in GitHub Actions to be
able to push changes in the same job.

Update commit configuration

Update user name and email configuration when making
the npm version patch commit to ensure the same user
who made the original push is also given credit for
the npm version patch commit.
Update release commit messages.
OSCAL React Library Release
OSCAL React Library Release
OSCAL React Library Release

Delete and recreate packages on push

Delete and recreate the oscal-react-library package on a push
to the repository, negating the need to update package.json
and package-lock.json files and make a second push prior to
publishing the package. Update the package.json and
package-lock.json files to an earlier version number as the
version numbers after 0.1.0 are no longer being used.

Update GitHub super linter

Newer versions of the super linter changed to using eslint for JSON
linting; however, our eslintrc doesn't specify the JSON plugin. This
adds it as a dependency and to the configuration file to ensure that the
plugin is available and JSON can be parsed correctly.

Adjust eslint configuration for example app

This ensures that the example app is captured correctly in the eslint
config and that the app complies with the linting requirements.

Update create-react-scripts

Update React Router and Scripts

This was a major upgrade for the react-router-dom package and required
some pretty fundamental changes to the way our routing and redirects
work. For the react-scripts, we just needed to add an additional eslint
config package to the package.json

Create UI for editing default labels

Created the UI for editing default control implementation
labels. This includes creating the appropriate partial
PATCH data.

Cleanup eslint-related packages

There are a ton of eslint packages in our `package-lock.json` that we
don't directly use and there are updates to several of them as well.
This updates them to the newest cohesive set (we can't move to eslint 8
yet) possible.

Fix some downgraded packages

A few packages were downgraded and should not have been. This puts them
back to the newest compatible version
Apply fixes for storybook + cra5

Restore eslint-plugin-jest to compatible version

We are using `create-react-app@^6.0.0` which has a peer dependency on
`eslint-plugin-jest@^24.0.0`. We were installing something like 26.1.3
which is outside of that spec. That resulted in dependency resolution
(and therefore, build) failures. This downgrade ensures that all our
plugins fall within a resolveable set of dependencies. The
`package-lock.json` is regenerated as part of this via deleting
`package-lock.json` and running `npm install` which may result in some
incidental changes to other packages' versions.

Oddly, these failures didn't start until more recently _after_ the PR
was merged; however, this does seem to be the root cause.

seems to lose its mind (well, not that command directly but something

the dev server).

For now, let's pin it to 0.11.0 so that people can actually develop and
work. And we can evaluate removing this. The conflicting version that
seems to be coming up at the moment is 0.13.0. We probably could have
picked that version too but this is what most the app was resolving and

This creates an `AppWrapper` function so that our `ThemeProvider` is the
root of the application and to ensure that `useStyles` is not called
_before_ that. By doing this migration, our `useStyles()` won't get
called until within the `App()` function, which is _after_

Implement quick fix for error handling

We have continued to have some issues with errors that occur during the
OSCALLoader (and OSCALLoaderForm) because of the structure of various
components and where the errors occur. This implements a quick fix to
push the errors down into a child component of OSCALLoader. That
component will then throw the error, which can be caught be the
ErrorBoundary because it occurs as a child of the ErrorBoundary. This
should continue to preserve the form and other UI elements.

This has some kinda nasty side effects. The error message in the console
will sorta mask the actual location where the error occurred (it will
look like it came from the `ErrorThrower`) unless the error itself got
logged before that (which seems to usually happen) or unless the error
actually occurs somewhere in `{result}` which we've handled pretty
correctly for the most part.

`ErrorThrower` is deprecated upon creation because wow I really don't
want to see this in other places in our code base.

fix: build fails when installing app dependencies (#650)

Something went wrong in the `package-lock.json` file for the example
application directory. This is causing unrelated workflows to fail. This
may be a bug in the upgrade-dependencies workflow, but it should not
cause issues with unrelated PRs (and it is). This is also a fix included
in some other dependency-related work that is going to take a minute to
get in, so breaking it out seems prudent.

Because the update to `eslint` is now causing build failures for rules
that were always being violated, this adds a bunch of ignores to
`.eslintrc.json` as well. I don't like that but since these were present
before, all we're doing is temporarily continuing to ignore them until
the other open PRs that address them are merged.

refactor: switch to a monorepo with lerna (#722)

This refactors the repository into a more typical monorepo setup. This
will eventually allow to add additional packages (perhaps an API client
or a package that exports OSCAL types for TypeScript). Along with this
refactoring, we've replaced `create-react-library` with `rollup` for the
React library and we use `craco` instead of raw `react-scripts` in the
Viewer app (to workaround some wonkiness with forbidden imports outside
of `src/`).

Along with this we get TypeScript!! Only one or two files have been
rewritten as part of this migration. That serves two purposes, first
that we can use TypeScript, and second that we can adopt it
incrementally.

We also have a `scripts/` directory which will allow us to store scripts
that we want that are too complex to just toss into `package.json`. I
would like to keep those scripts limited to Bash (all our users should
have access to a basic Bash environment) or to TypeScript (we install
`ts-node` as a dev dependency in the root repo).

`lerna` is used as the tool to manage our monorepo. A lot of features
are now built into the `npm` workspaces features; however, `lerna` gives
us some nice ability to manage references between repos and to run
commands against all of them (and look at how nice that is for
`scripts/watch-viewer`!)

The tests are all still `jest` and our linting rules remain largely the
same. Tests should be run in the individual packages for now;
functionally for the majority of our work, this means that you need to
be in `packages/oscal-react-library` in order to run its tests for
example. For commands that do work across all packages without any
dependencies (for now, just `lint`) those can be run across all packages
from the root.

If you do want to run across all packages, `lerna exec --stream` is a
good friend; additionally, its `--scope` and `--include-dependencies`
and `--include-dependents` arguments may be good friends.

You _do not_ need to install `lerna` globally (although you may find it
useful to do so). You can use `npx lerna` (as the example in
`scripts/watch-viewer` does).

Closes: #732 
Closes: #403
Closes: #596 
Closes: #493

feat: automatically generate OSCAL types from JSON Schema (#765)

This adds a new package `@easydynamics/oscal-types` that will convert
the underlying OSCAL JSON schema to TypeScipt type definitions. It also
replaces two existing instances of type information in
`oscal-react-library`
with these new types: Properties and BackMater within `oscal-utils`.

The types are represented _literally_. This includes things like
`media-type` rather than making it the friendlier `mediaType`.
Additionally, to encourage good hygiene, all types are represented as
`readonly`.

Closes: #763
